# Intercostal Muscles

> The intercostal muscles occupy the **11 intercostal spaces** between adjacent ribs. They assist respiration and stabilise the thoracic wall. Each space contains three layers — external, internal, and innermost — with the **neurovascular bundle** (vein–artery–nerve, VAN) running in the **costal groove** beneath each rib.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Muscular System]], [[Respiratory System]]
- Contained between: [[Ribs]] (inferior border of upper rib to superior border of lower rib)
- Neurovascular bundle: Intercostal vein + artery + nerve (T1–T11) — in costal groove **under rib** (VAN order, superior to inferior)
- Blood supply: Posterior intercostal arteries (from descending [[Aorta]] / [[Subclavian Artery]]); anterior intercostal arteries (from internal thoracic artery)

## 🔬 Three Layers

| Muscle | Fibre Direction | Action |
|--------|----------------|--------|
| **External intercostal** | Oblique downward-forward ("hands in pockets") | **Inspiration** — elevates ribs → ↑ thoracic volume |
| **Internal intercostal** | Oblique downward-backward (perpendicular to external) | **Forced expiration** — depresses ribs |
| **Innermost intercostal** | Same as internal; deep to neurovascular bundle | Same as internal intercostal |

**Neurovascular bundle** runs between internal and innermost layers — insert needle above lower rib to avoid the bundle (thoracentesis, intercostal drain).

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Intercostal nerve block** — anaesthesia for rib fractures, thoracotomy; inject inferior to rib (to anaesthetise nerve below)
- **Chest drain insertion** — 4th–5th ICS, anterior axillary line; over **superior border** of lower rib to avoid VAN
- **Thoracentesis** — needle inserted over superior border of lower rib in costodiaphragmatic recess (8th ICS, mid-axillary line)
- **Intercostal neuralgia** — post-herpetic, traumatic; burning/shooting pain in dermatomal distribution

